SIMPLE: fortify
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fortify
<hw>For"ti*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Fortified</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Fortifying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>fortifier</ets>, L. <ets>fortificare</ets>; <ets>fortis</ets>
strong + <ets>-ficare</ets> (in comp.) to make. See <er>Fort</er>, and
<er>-fy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To add strength to; to strengthen;
to confirm; to furnish with power to resist attack.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Timidity was <qex>fortified</qex> by pride.</q>
<rj><qau>Gibbon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pride came to the aid of fancy, and both combined to
<qex>fortify</qex> his resolution.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To strengthen and secure by forts or batteries, or
by surrounding with a wall or ditch or other military works; to render
defensible against an attack by hostile forces.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fortify</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fortify
<hw>For"ti*fy</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To raise defensive
works.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fortilage</ent>⟦br⟧
